rnd_spending <- read.csv("API_GB.XPD.RSDV.GD.ZS_DS2_en_csv_v2_1678501/API_GB.XPD.RSDV.GD.ZS_DS2_en_csv_v2_1678501.csv", skip = 4)

Country-level information on studies

# summarizing information on the country of study/country of author for each study
country_flow_summary <- site_study_main %>% 
  filter(!is.na(author1_country)) %>% 
  filter(author1_country != "") %>%
  filter(!is.na(country_of_study)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(author1_local)) %>% 
  filter(country_of_study != "") %>% 
  group_by(study_id, author1_country, author1_local, country_of_study) %>% 
  summarise() %>% 
  ungroup()

# joining the above df with area of mangroves in the country (hectares), gdp of the country, R&D spending of the country, and the nature index of the country
country_flow_summary2 <- country_flow_summary %>% 
  left_join(mangrove_area, by = c("country_of_study" = "..Country")) %>% 
  left_join(gdp_2014, by = c("country_of_study" = "Country.Name")) %>% 
  left_join(rnd_spending, by = "Country.Code") %>% 
  left_join(nature_index, by = c("Country.Code" = "iso")) %>% 
  mutate(rnd = rowMeans(select(., X2014.y:X2018), na.rm =  TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(country_of_study, ha, Country.Code, X2014.x, rnd, AC) %>% 
  rename(gdp = X2014.x) %>% 
  summarise(no_of_papers = n()) %>% 
  filter(country_of_study != "NP") %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(!is.na(ha))

# changing mangrove area (ha) to integer 
country_flow_summary2$ha <- as.integer(country_flow_summary2$ha)

# adding transformed columns; the rationale for the transformation is provided in the section where the assumptions of the linear regression are checked
country_flow_summary2 <- country_flow_summary2 %>% 
  mutate(log_no_of_papers = log(no_of_papers),
         log_AC = log(AC),
         log_ha = log(ha),
         log_gdp = log(gdp))


ggpairs(country_flow_summary2 %>% select(ha, no_of_papers, rnd, gdp, AC))

# AC (article count = nature index) correlates with rnd but not much with the GDP; rnd correlates with both GDP and AC. 
# So, we can use AC, which allows us to also use the GDP information.

# using AC would not imply circular thinking: AC is based on a large number of natural sciences research including all countries (many of which don't even have mangroves), and the portion of mangrove ecology research that forms a part of the AC is negligibly small.

Linear Regression Models

# creating a linear regression model with only 1 explanatory variable, to preliminarily assess the explanatory power of each variable

model1 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_AC)
model2 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_ha)
model3 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_gdp)
model4 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ rnd)

# so far, we can already see 'AC' and 'rnd' having a much greater r^2 than ha and gdp.

# now we move on to multiple linear regression models. we will be deciding among one of these models to be our best explanatory model. 
# we have 2 sets of multiple linear regression models. (1) those that include log_AC and (2) those that include rnd.
# we do not use both of these explanatory variables together in order to prevent multicolinearity.

# models 5, 6, 9, 10, and 13 include log_AC,
# models 7,8, 11, 12 and 14 include rnd.

model5 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_AC + log_ha)
model6 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_AC * log_ha)
model7 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ rnd + log_ha)
model8 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ rnd * log_ha)
model9 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_AC + log_gdp)
model10 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_AC * log_gdp)
model11 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ rnd + log_gdp)
model12 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ rnd * log_gdp)
model13 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ log_AC + log_ha + log_gdp)
model14 <- lm(data = country_flow_summary2, formula = log_no_of_papers ~ rnd + log_gdp + log_ha)

# we get the highest r^2 value among 'log_AC' models in models 5 and 6. these include log_AC and log_ha (mangrove area) and differ in whether they include interaction effect or not.
# similarly, we get the highest r^2 value among 'rnd' models in models 5 and 6. these include rnd and log_ha (mangrove area) and differ in whether they include interaction effect or not.

# we use AIC test to test the models. we only use AIC tests for the higher r^2 value ones, and we test models that have separate group of explanatory variables separately
AIC(model5, model6)
AIC(model7, model8)
# the difference between the AIC values for the interaction and non-interaction models (in both cases) is very low. Further, looking at the summary data for the models, we see that the interaction model doesn't have significant 'p-values' for its coefficients. Also, the change in r^2 values among the interaction and non-interaction models is negligible.

# With these factors in consideration, we consider the non-interaction models.
# Among model5 and model7, we include model 5 since its r^2 value is around 0.70 while that of model7 is around 0.49.

# However, the two models both show the greater explanatory power of including the mangrove area (ha). Although mangrove area (ha) on its own doesn't explain the variation in numbers of paper at all, in a multiple linear regression model with the nature index (log_AC) or R&D (rnd), the inclusion of mangrove area (ha) helps explain a greater amount of variation. So, even though not as important as log_AC or rnd, the mangrove area still is a valuable explanatory variable for the regression models.

# In all these models, GDP has virtually no explanatory power in explaining the variation of the y-variable, whether it be in a single-explanatory variable linear regression or in a multiple linear regression. The addition of GDP to the other 2 explanatory variables doesn't lead to much difference in r^2 values, so we do not include GDP in the final model.

#--- WHAT DOES THE MODELS SUGGEST?
# The number of papers coming from countries seems to depend greatly on the general trend of research in the country, rather than mangrove specific factors. Although the number of hectares of mangrove present does help explain the number of papers coming from the country, most of the variation is explained by the nature-index. 

# For the rnd case, the number of hectares of mangroves does help in providing a greater explanation power, as seen in the log_no_of_papers ~ rnd + log_ha case, where the addition of log_ha increased r^2 from 0.2678 to 0.4871 (even though in the  log_no_of_papers ~ ha, 'ha' had no explanatory power).

Question 2: How well are the different explanatory variables studied?

Completeness Index for Variables

gives information on how well a variable has been studied, depending on how complete the variable is in terms of life_stages, no_of_species, no_of_countries (a proxy for geographical spread), and no_of_papers. All these are given equal weight. Z-score is also calculated to see how the values for completeness_index compare across the variables.

study_expl_var_matrix <- paths %>% 
  filter(expl_var_l != "tree_species") %>% 
  distinct(study_id, species_id, LH_stage, expl_var_l) %>% 
  filter(species_id != "NA") %>% 
  filter(LH_stage != "NA") %>% 
  left_join(site_study_main %>% distinct(study_id, country_of_study) %>% select(study_id, country_of_study)) %>% 
  group_by(expl_var_l) %>% 
  summarise(life_stages = n_distinct(LH_stage),
            no_of_species = n_distinct(species_id),
            no_of_countries = n_distinct(country_of_study),
            no_of_papers = n_distinct(study_id))
            

study_expl_var_matrix %>% 
  mutate(completeness_index = (life_stages/max(life_stages) + no_of_species/max(no_of_species) + no_of_countries/max(no_of_countries))/3 * (no_of_papers/max(no_of_papers))) %>% 
  mutate(z_scores = (completeness_index - mean(completeness_index))/sd(completeness_index)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(completeness_index))

Supplementary: Possible Analysis in the Future - PCA

# this is an effort at carrying out a PCA for the given dataset. Given the limited number of papers (only around 100), the PCA will likely not show any result, since there are almost around 20 columns. However, we hope a similar analysis can be carried out in the future, with more datapoints, which might help explain the variance in the papers studied based on the variables that they study.

# Each row of the matrix created is one paper, whereas the columns are the explanatory variables.
# Since the explanatory variables were categorical, we decided to convert them to binary variables and put them as columns. If the value for a specific column is '1', it means that variable is studied in the paper. if it is '0' it means the variable is not studied in the paper.

# creating the matrix
study_expl_var_l_matrix <- paths %>% 
  filter(expl_var_l != "tree_species") %>% 
  #filter(box_resp == "4") %>% 
  distinct(study_id, expl_var_l) %>%
  left_join(expl_reclassification, by = c("expl_var_l" = "..expl_var_l_initial")) %>% 
  mutate(expl_var_l_y.n = 1) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = expl_var_l_broader, values_from = expl_var_l_y.n, values_fill = 0) %>% 
  select(-expl_var_l) %>% 
  select(-`NA`) %>% 
  group_by(study_id) %>% 
  summarise_all(funs(sum))


study_expl_var_l_matrix.pca <- prcomp(study_expl_var_l_matrix[, -c(1)])
summary(study_expl_var_l_matrix.pca)
